    affiliation: "Columbia University in the City of New York"
date-released: "2026"
url: "https://github.com/Sophie-S-Z/CSUREMM3-2026"
abstract: >
  There is no mathematical basis for why Alzheimer's disease tau pathology
  consistently targets certain brain regions, such as the entorhinal cortex,
  before spreading elsewhere. This project ranks brain regions by their
  dynamical resistance to destabilization rather than by structural
  connectivity alone, using network control theory applied to a
  criticality-linearized Wilson-Cowan neural mass model built on 83-region
  HCP structural connectomes. Across 351 ADNI subjects, this "critical lever"
  ranking predicts where tau pathology accumulates (the hardest-to-tip
  regions), the opposite of where amyloid accumulates (easy-to-tip hub
  regions), even after controlling for hub degree. We then use this ranking,
  alongside structural and empirical alternatives, to inform a personalized
  Fisher-Kolmogorov reaction-diffusion model of tau spread, calibrated to
  longitudinal tau-PET data from 43 subjects, and compare five region-targeted
  protection strategies in simulation. Protecting regions with the highest
  existing tau burden reduced simulated whole-brain tau accumulation more
  than protecting dynamically fragile or highly connected regions. This
  repository provides a computational framework for identifying and
  evaluating candidate brain regions for future anti-tau intervention
  targets.
